@endnode
@Node WHAT "What is it?"
    The latest version of "The Wheel of Fortune" received MANY, MANY, MANY
enhancements, changes, additions, etc... that should prove to make this the
most POWERFUL version of "WOF" being run on ANY Bulletin Board Software for
ANY Computer Platform! (Really! Honest! hehe)

    This README file, along with others located in the "WoFortune/Guides/"
directory use external links to each other for some of the buttons. These
links are hard-coded in each document to SPECIFICALLY find a specific file
in the "pfiles:WoFortune/Guides/" directory, so it may become neccessary
to manually edit these links if you stored WOF in some other location.
@endnode
@Node INSTALL "How to Install It?"
   Although the new "WOF_Install" script should be all that is needed to
get the game up and running on your BBS's, here's a rundown on what needs
to be done if you don't trust installation scripts. (Paranoid, eh?!?)

    You will need the following commands located somewhere in your valid
PATH assignment, or your C: directory, whichever is easier:

            rename \ These are used for maintaining the three
            delete / WOF Game Logs(In Ascii, ANSI, & IBM-ANSI)
            sort   - Is used to keep Players list alphabetized.

 1: The "WoFortune.Config" file and "WoFortune/" directory should both be
    placed in your PFILES: directory.

 2: The following line should be added to your "sys.welcome" file, or
    somewhere else in your bbs's logon sequence:

            {#0 pfiles:WoFortune/Loader}
            ^                   ^
        Control-Q            See NOTE under Number 3 below.

 3: The following commands should be added to the bottom of your Menu # 2,
    Available Everywhere Commands, in your "cnet:bbsmenu" file:

        WOF         `1-  |   {#0 PFiles:WoFortune/Loader}
        WOFC        `1-  |   {#0 PFiles:WoFortune/UserConfig}
        WOFS        `31  |   {#0 PFiles:WoFortune/Config}
        WOFM        `31  |   {#0 PFiles:WoFortune/Maint}
                     ^       ^
         Access Groups       Replace with a Control Q character.

NOTE: Starting with v6.40, the "WoFortune.Loader" file has been renamed to
      just "Loader", and is now stored in your "WoFortune/" directory. If
      you're upgrading from a previous version of Wheel of Fortune, make
      sure to make this change to both your BBSMENU and SYS.WELCOME files!

 4: Use the "AL" (Add List) CNet Command to create a directory in one of
    your PFILE areas where you can ADOPT numerous files.  When it asks you
    for the "unique filename" for directory, use the "pfiles:WoFortune/"
    directory to make it use the included directory.  This will save you
    from having to create another directory, simply to hold CNet's "data/"
    directory.

 5: Use the "AO" (Adopt Orphans) command to adopt the following files into
    the new directory you created in # 4 above:

        pfiles:WoFortune/Loader     - The WOF Game Progress Indicator, and
                                      Game Loader.

        pfiles:WoFortune/Game.ASC   - The Ascii Game Version (No Color or
                                      IBM Graphics are used.)

        pfiles:WoFortune/Game.ANS   - The Ansi Game Version (Uses Color,
                                      but no IBM Graphics are used.)

        pfiles:WoFortune/Game.IBM   - The IBM Game Version (Uses both Color
                                      and IBM Graphics!)

        pfiles:WoFortune/UserConfig - The Config file your USERS can use to
                                      specify how they wish the game to be
                                      played for THEM.

        pfiles:WoFortune/Config     - The Config Module (Allows SysOp to
                                      define exactly how the Game will act,
                                      feel, and perform!)

        pfiles:WoFortune/Maint      - The Maint Module (Allows SysOp to
                                      weed players, or reset the game.)

        pfiles:WoFortune/SetUp      - The SetUp Module (Sets up Game Files
                                      for the 1st Time you play the Game.)

    The "Loader" file, "Game.???" modules, and "UserConfig" file should be
    added as MULTI-Use Arexx Pfiles that can be run by any users on your
    bbs, using the same Access Groupings you specified in # 3 above.

    NOTE TO MULTI-LINE SYSOPS: It is now 100% safe for your users to try
    and load the "Game." Modules directly. Checks for Open/Closed status,
    as well as "Port Use" have been included, starting in the v6.1 modules.

    The "Config", "Maint", and "SetUp" files should be added as EXCLUSIVE
    Use Only Arexx pfiles that only the SYSOP has access to use. It would
    NOT be wise to give your users access to these files!

 6: A new file, "WOF_News", has been included within the "WoFortune/" main
    directory. This file is suitable for use as a NEWS file you may wish to
    run on your bbs. To install it, simply enter your NEWS area, then use
    the AO(Adopt Orphans) command to adopt the file at path:

        "pfiles:WoFortune/WOF_News"  (remember, use YOUR designated path)

    Be sure to ADOPT the file, versus ADDING it, else you'll be asked if
    you want to load it into CNet's Draw Editor, which is NOT what you want
    to do. (In fact, you do not want to load this file into ANY of CNet's
    editors, as this will result in the ansi coding becoming corrupted).

 7: You may wish to colorize the following lines in BBSTEXT, as ONE or MORE
    of these lines will be used whenever a player plays WOF. Note that
    these lines are from the v3.05c BBSTEXT file:

        910:    \n1Now muffling
        911:    \n1Now listening to

        914:    \n1Now monitoring
        915:    \n1No longer monitoring

        917:     all ports.\n1
                ^
                Space

        920:    \n1\c6**** System Message\n2\a1\@1

    These lines deal with the MUFFLE, MONITOR, and SYSTEM OLM features of
    WOF.

    NOTE: The \@1 at the end of line 920 should be REMOVED from that line
          if you will be using the OLM features, so that COLORED OLM
          Messages may be sent to the users.

 7: Due to an inconsistency between the SysOp's LOCAL screen versus REGULAR
    remote screens, you may need to adjust the VERTICAL "dot rows" setting
    of your "Prefs/ScreenMode" Preferences Utility if using WOF on a non-
    interlaced screen. Normally this setting is equal to "200". You will
    need to adjust this to a setting of "203" or "205" in order for certain
    modules(namely the CONFIG) to be displayed on your screen properly.

    This is the reason some of you may have noticed that the CONFIG Screen
    would seemingly move UP the screen ONE too many lines, making the LOOK
    and FEEL of the CONFIG horrendous! This "quirk" in CNet only appears on
    the LOCAL Screen of Non-Interlaced 640x200 screens, and is NOT present
    when using CONFIG from REMOTE using these settings.

    NOTE: This is the reason some of my other programs(like Yacht-Zee) may
          seem to NOT be working correctly as well. It should also be noted
          that this is a bug in CNet, and NOT in this or other game files.
@endnode
@Node SETUP "Setting Up The Game"
    Before the first player uses the game, you will want to configure the
game to run exactly the way YOU wish to run it. The first file you should
use is the CONFIG module. Although the CONFIG Module can be loaded from
within any of the "Game" Modules, it is a good idea to use it externally
the FIRST time you use it.

    Please refer to the new "@{"CONFIG_README!" link "pfiles:WoFortune/Guides/CONFIG.GUIDE/Main"}" file NOW for further info
concerning the CONFIG Module.
@endnode
@Node START "Starting the First Game"

    After you have Configured the game to play the way YOU want it to, all
that's left for you to do is initialize the first game. To do this, you
will need to run the "SetUp" module. You can do this in one of two ways:

    - Run it directly out of your pfiles directory.

    - Run one of the "Game" modules.

    If run directly out of your pfiles, the game will be set up and you
will be deposited back at the same prompt you started it from, but if you
select to run one of the "Game" modules, the game will be set up and you'll
be able to play the game as the first player ever! It's YOUR choice!

    The "SetUp" program doesn't need any input from you, so unless you're
using an 030/040, you can go and catch a cup of coffee, use the bathroom,
etc, while it does its work:

    - All additional game support files are created.
    - The Puzzle file is thoroughly shuffled and cut.
    - The first Game is chosen, encrypted, and saved to disk.
@endnode
@Node WHO "Reading the WHO Displays"
    Depending on WHICH WOF program is currently loaded, different things
will be printed in the WHO Display and/or Control Window as follows:

"WOF Loader" ------- The Wheel of Fortune "Loader" Module is loaded.

"WOF ASC Game" ----- The "Game.ASC" (ASCII Version) Module is loaded.

"WOF ANS Game" ----- The "Game.ANS" (ANSI Version) Module is loaded.

"WOF IBM Game" ----- The "Game.IBM" (IBM-ANSI Version) Module is loaded.

"WOF Bonus Round" -- The "Bonus Round" being played by a "Game." Module.

"WOF User Config" -- The "User Config" Module is being used by a player.

"WOF Main Config" -- The "Config" Module is loaded.

"WOF Puz. Grower" -- A Maint User is Adding Puzzles to "PuzData" file.

"WOF 6.41 SETUP" --- The "SetUp"  Module is loaded.

"WOF Maintenance" -- The "Maint"  Module is loaded.

"WOF Game EDIT" ---- The "Game Editor"    (In Registered Versions Only!)

"WOF Puzzle EDIT" -- The "Puzzle Editor"  (In Registered Versions Only!)

"WOF Reg. EDIT" ---- The "Reg Editor"     (In Registered Versions Only!)

"WOF Color EDIT" --- The "Color Editor"   (In Registered Versions Only!)

"WOF Hist. EDIT" --- The "History Editor" (In Registered Versions Only!)

    The "Loader" file checks to see which, if any, ports have the first
three letters "WOF" as their WHO Display, and if any other ports DO, then
the present port is not allowed to LOAD(Play) Wheel of Fortune, v6.41.
    (Note that v7.0 will allow multiple games, like in Global War!)

NOTE: Remember, in v6.41, this same checking is now BUILT-IN to the "Game"
      Modules, so it is 100% safe for MULTI-LINE Systems to allow the
      "Game" Modules to be loaded directly out of the pfiles section!
@endnode
@Node DIFF "Differences In The Versions"
    Although great care was taken to make sure the three versions of the
game PLAY alike, there ARE some differences between them you may want to
be made aware of...

           @{" ASCII Version " link ASC}     @{" ANSI Version " link ANS}     @{" IBM-ANSI Version " link IBM}
@endnode
@Node ASC "What's in the ASCII version?"
    - This version uses NO ANSI CODES whatsoever. It also does NOT use any
      of the following MCI Commands: \c, \f0, \>, \<, \^, and \!, however
      MCI Color Commands are used when writing to the LOGS, although there
      is also a straight-Ascii log which is created too.
    - This version also does NOT use ANY IBM Graphic Characters. ALL the
      graphics were accomplished using standard Ascii (Keyboard) graphics.
    - This version does NOT support the "rotating" wheel graphic. Also,
      because of the inability to HOME the cursor WITHOUT clearing the
      screen, the Wedge Graphics that ARE used appear on the screen after
      screen clears, although without MCI's & ANSI's to interpret, this
      pause is fairly negligible.
    - This version also does NOT use(or offer to use) the On-Screen
      Timer in the Bonus Rounds, because of the ANSI Nature of it's
      coding scheme.
    - Because of the lack of any color commands, etc., this version of the
      game is VERY fast in it's execution. 300 to 2400 bauders may enjoy
      playing this version over the other two, if COLOR is not an issue...
@endnode
@Node ANS "What's in the ANSI version?"
    - All MCI & ANSI Codes were FAIR GAME in this version. The only thing
      missing from this version are IBM Graphic Characters.
    - This version was written with the 8-Color user in mind. High
      intensity colors WERE used within the program, but not in such a way
      as to be invisible if played in 8-Color Mode. I even played it once
      in 4-Color mode, and although not as visually appealing, it IS
      PLAYABLE.
    - This version is the second fastest version available, next to the
      ASCII version. This is for those users who don't mind NOT having the
      IBM Graphics, but WOULD like some COLOR in the game. These could be
      your 64/128 users, TRS users, etc...
@endnode
@Node IBM "What's in the IBM-ANSI version?"
    - I spared NOTHING in this version! It has EVERYTHING! Graphics, 16
      Awesome Colors, and rock solid coding, not to mention it's FUN as
      all hell to PLAY! hehe.
@endnode
@Node TREBOR "Differences Between MY v5.0-v6.x & Trebor's Previous Versions"
    Although I tried to make this game as close to Trebors as possible, I
did make some changes, which I think really make this thing sparkle:

    - This version uses a Wheel format which, with the exception of the
      SURPRISE, is identical to the Board Game & TV Show.
    - Certain "realism" routines were added to the way the wheel spins, for
      example, on the TV show, the wheel must spin around at LEAST once for
      the value to be valid. These "little" kinds of things were added just
      to make the game play more like the TV show.
    - The Wedge Graphics in ALL THREE VERSIONS are completely NEW. Trebors
      were nice looking, but were rather large, and took a while to print
      on the screen, especially at 2400 baud. I also didn't like the idea
      that the screen cleared right after the wheel stopped spinning. Both
      of these concerns were addressed in MY versions.
    - The Game LOGS are COMPLETELY NEW to ANY WOF Game! I got the idea
      from the Paragon Version of Global War(See the NEWS Files)...
    - In previous versions of the game, if a player ENTERED the file, but
      didn't actually PLAY(Either Spin, Buy Vowel, or Guess Puzzle), it
      would STILL mark them as being the Last Player. This version will
      only tag the user as the Last Player if they actually PLAYED the
      game.
    - I did some spell-checking, editing, weeding, etc of the main listing
      of puzzles, plus added the 100 that were found in the WOF Board Game,
      and also included the 100 Registered Puzzles from the v5.? series.
      (The Registered v6.3 SysOps will be getting OVER 2000 Puzzles!)
    - This version ENCRYPTS the Puzzles file, so even the SYSOP can enjoy
      playing the game, as unless they know Arexx, there won't be an easy
      way to DECRYPT the puzzles.
    - My versions now have the ability to MUFFLE all ports from receiving
      incoming OLM's, and can send Broadcast SYSTEM Messages alerting the
      other ports OF this fact. OLM's can also be sent whenever a player
      has WON a Regular or BONUS Round Game!
@endnode
@Node FILES "Other files created once the game has started..."
Within the archive you've unpacked, you have these files:

    - WoFortune.Config       \
    - WoFortune Directory/    \
        - Game.ASC             \
        - Game.ANS              > Already discussed above.
        - Game.IBM             /
        - Loader              /
        - Config             /
        - UserConfig        /
        - Maint            /
        - SetUp___________/
        - Docs.ASC        \
        - Docs.ANS         > Graphic Specific Instruction Files.
        - Docs.IBM________/

        - PuzData ------------- 350 Encrypted Puzzles.
        - OLM_Proc ------------ WOF's Background OLM Processor.
        - WOF_News ------------ An ANSI screen to use as a NEWS file!
        - Grow ---------------- Maint file used to add puzzles to PuzData.
        - README! ------------- This AmigaGuide file.
        - @{"CONFIG_README" link "pfiles:WoFortune/Guides/CONFIG.GUIDE/Main"} ------- Guide describing WOF's CONFIG Program!
        - @{"HISTORY!" link "pfiles:WoFortune/Guides/HISTORY.GUIDE/Main"} ------------ Changes, Additions, etc.
        - @{"REGISTER!" link "pfiles:WoFortune/Guides/REGISTER.GUIDE/Main"} ----------- How & Why You Should Register This Game!
        - Graphics/ Dir ------- Holds ASC/ANS/IBM Graphic Picture Files!
        - Register/ Dir ------- ANSI Screen Shots from the REGISTERED WOF
                                Utilities (That are already completed!)

After the game has started, these other files will be created:

        - @{"GameData" link "pfiles:WoFortune/Guides/PROGRAMMERS.GUIDE/GAMEDATA"} ------ Holds data for the current game.
        - @{"Stats" link "pfiles:WoFortune/Guides/PROGRAMMERS.GUIDE/STATS"} --------- Holds the Hall of Fame data.
        - @{"Players" link "pfiles:WoFortune/Guides/PROGRAMMERS.GUIDE/PLAYERS"} ------- Holds info on ALL Players of WOF6.
        - @{"LastPlayer" link "pfiles:WoFortune/Guides/PROGRAMMERS.GUIDE/LASTPLAYER"} ---- Holds info on the LAST Player of the Game.
        - @{"LastReset" link "pfiles:WoFortune/Guides/PROGRAMMERS.GUIDE/LASTRESET"} ----- Holds date of last Game Reset.
        - @{"Winner" link "pfiles:WoFortune/Guides/PROGRAMMERS.GUIDE/WINNER"} -------- Holds data of the last WOF6 Winner.
        - @{"Winners" link "pfiles:WoFortune/Guides/PROGRAMMERS.GUIDE/WINNERS"} ------- Holds the Last "x" Winner's Data.
        - @{"BWinner" link "pfiles:WoFortune/Guides/PROGRAMMERS.GUIDE/BWINNER"} ------- Holds data on the last BONUS Winner.
        - @{"BWinners" link "pfiles:WoFortune/Guides/PROGRAMMERS.GUIDE/BWINNERS"} ------ Holds the Last "x" Bonus Winners Data.
        - @{"Millionaires" link "pfiles:WoFortune/Guides/PROGRAMMERS.GUIDE/MILLIONAIRES"} -- Holds Players > $1,000,000 in Regular Play!
        - @{"BMillionaires" link "pfiles:WoFortune/Guides/PROGRAMMERS.GUIDE/BMILLIONAIRES"} - Holds Players > $1,000,000 in Bonus Play!
        - @{"Bankers" link "pfiles:WoFortune/Guides/PROGRAMMERS.GUIDE/BANKERS"} ------- Holds ALL TIME BEST WOF Players Listing!
        - Log.OLD.ASC \
        - Log.OLD.ANS  > Holds Game Events from LAST Game.
        - Log.OLD.IBM /
        - Log.NEW.ASC \
        - Log.NEW.ANS  > Holds Game Events from CURRENT Game.
        - Log.NEW.IBM /
        - NewPuz ------- Holds puzzles created by user winners.
                         See the @{"REGISTER!" link "pfiles:WoFortune/Guides/REGISTER.GUIDE/Main"} file for more info!
@endnode
@Node OTHER "Other things you might want to know about..."
    Whenever you restart the game(using the "SetUp" Module, or by deleting
the "GameData" file and running one of the "Game" Modules), you'll see some
text files being created, followed by the "Mixing" info. The puzzles are
"shuffled" randomly seven times, in two steps. The "shuffle" mode is when
half the puzzles are randomly rearranged. The "cutting" mode is when the
first half and the last half of the puzzles are swapped. This enables the
next "shuffle" mode to be able to pick puzzles that were on the ENDS of the
range(and most probably weren't randomly selected the first time). I've
found this to be a fairly reliable way of insuring a nice randomity to the
shuffle.

    If the users start complaining about an "unsolvable" puzzle, which
might be the result of a spelling error or something of that nature, the
SysOp, or other designated "Maint" user has access to the "C" command off
the Main Menu to CANCEL the current game. A new game will be autogenerated
in this event.

    There is one other "hidden" command, but I'll let you figure out WHAT
it is, and WHAT it does. It is also only available to "Maint" users.

    When the LAST Puzzle in the list has been solved, the program will
start again at Puzzle # 1, but it will NOT reshuffle the puzzles. If this
is your intent, please RESET the game by either running "SetUp" or deleting
the "pfiles:WoFortune/GameData" file and running a "Game." module file.

    The Bonus Puzzles work in reverse order from the Puzzles, whereas the
Puzzles start at 1, then use 2, then 3, the Bonus Puzzles will start at
350, then go to 349, 348, etc. This was done so that the puzzle used for
the BONUS Round doesn't also turn out to be the puzzle used in the next
regular Game.

    In the WOF6 Logon Display Window, where the Guessed Letters are shown,
an arrow pointing to the LEFT will be shown in FRONT of the letters if too
many letters have been guessed to be shown in this area. Only the most
recent guessed letters will be shown, along with the arrow, like this:

                        Guessed: <---W-R-S-T-A-F-G-I
@endnode
@Node BUGS "What About Bugs?"
    This file has been, by far, one of my more ambitious projects, and
although I've gone to GREAT LENGTHS to insure this file is as bug free as
possible, I'd be kidding myself if I were to guarantee you there are NO
bugs within at least ONE of these files.

    What I WILL guarantee, however, is that if you DO encounter a bug, or
some other quirky nature within any of the command files, please alert me
to the specific details which produced the bug(especially which command
file it was that GAVE you the error), and I will have a fix for you within
24 hours!

    This version now utilizes my newest error-checking routines. I no
longer am using the "wof.errors" file, so you can delete that file from
your designated WOF directory if you see it there. The new routines now
write custom built error strings to either your "ArexxSays" log or your
"calls" log if you do not use an "ArexxSays" log. The error messages are
complete and should be very readable, without data being chopped off that
could help in debugging!

    Lastly, this version(minus bug fix updates) WILL be the last
UNREGISTERED version I release. Both the Head to Head Module, as well as
v7.0 (with the multiple games settings) will be available to REGISTERED
OWNERS only. This project has left the scope of being a "fun/for enjoyment
only" purposes, and is turning out to be a hell of a lot of work. I lost
all source files in the v6.40 writing 2 days before I was ready to release
them when I was hit with a devisating hard drive crash, and had to start
from scratch.

    Well, enough soap-boxing. Please ENJOY this work, and if the Registered
files sound appealing, please read the "REGISTER" file for the details on
registering this program! Thanks for reading this!

                                                    - Dotoran, David Weeks.
